    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-20T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-20T14:00:00-05:00" n="870"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d870">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111 A.R./1103: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Des Portes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-20T13:00:00-06:00"
                            >May 20, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 3:56 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. The Foreign Minister<note n="33a" xml:id="d870fn33a">Carlos Salazar.</note>
                    has just shown me a memorandum presented today by the German Minister<note
                        n="33b" xml:id="d870fn33b">Otto Reinebeck, German Minister in Central
                        America.</note> with regard to the Argentine non-belligerency proposal<note
                        n="34" xml:id="d870fn34">See <ref target="#pg_743">pp. 743</ref> ff.</note>
                    and the protest of the American Republics made upon the initiative of Uruguay
                    against the invasion of the Low Countries.<note n="35" xml:id="d870fn35">See
                            <ref target="#pg_184">pp. 184</ref> ff.</note> After defending the
                    German invasion of these countries the memorandum goes on to say that the German
                    Government would consider it “a markedly unfriendly act” if Guatemala should
                    join in any such moves, which the memorandum states are propaganda inspired by
                    the personal hatred of certain foreign politicians.</p>
                <p>The Legation would be grateful to know if a similar threat has been presented to
                    the other American Republics and the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Des Portes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
